Learning Check 12.1

Go ahead and run a regression that models the log10-transformed prices as the outcome variable and uses log10-transformed square footage as the explanatory variable. Note that this is a basic regression (and not a multiple regression).

price_model <- lm(log10_price ~ log10_size, data= house_prices)
get_regression_table(price_model)

Learning Check 12.2

Use infer() to calculate a 95% confidence interval for the slope parameter in the previous regression.

house_prices %>%  summarize(stat = mean(log10_price))
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##    stat
##   <dbl>
## 1  5.67
bootstrap_distribution_prices <- house_prices %>% 
  specify(response = log10_price) %>% generate(reps = 1000, replace = TRUE, type="bootstrap") %>% calculate(stat = "mean")

bootstrap_distribution_prices
## # A tibble: 1,000 x 2
##    replicate  stat
##        <int> <dbl>
##  1         1  5.67
##  2         2  5.67
##  3         3  5.67
##  4         4  5.67
##  5         5  5.66
##  6         6  5.67
##  7         7  5.67
##  8         8  5.67
##  9         9  5.67
## 10        10  5.67
## #  with 990 more rows
percentile_ci_prices <- bootstrap_distribution_prices %>% 
  get_confidence_interval(level = 0.95, type = "percentile")

percentile_ci_prices
## # A tibble: 1 x 2
##   `2.5%` `97.5%`
##    <dbl>   <dbl>
## 1   5.66    5.67
visualise(bootstrap_distribution_prices) + 
  shade_confidence_interval(endpoints = percentile_ci_prices)

Learning Check 12.3

Hypothesis tests around the slope. Use infer() to generate a hypothesis around the relationship between log10_price and log10_size. Visualize the resulting distribution and shade the p value associated with your observed statistic. What is the value of p?

null_dist_prices <- house_prices %>%specify(response = log10_price) %>% 
  hypothesize(null = "point", mu = 5.67) %>% generate(reps = 1000, type = "bootstrap") %>% 
  calculate(stat = "mean")

pval <- null_dist_prices %>% get_pvalue(obs_stat = 1.054, direction = "less")

pval
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
